Implementation details:
- Implement an `error` module with a central `Error` enum and specific variants per phase:
  ```rust
  #[derive(Debug)]
  pub enum Error {
      Parse(ParseError),
      Layout(LayoutError),
      Render(RenderError),
  }

  #[derive(Debug)]
  pub struct ParseError {
      pub kind: ParseErrorKind,
      pub line: usize,
      pub column: usize,
      pub message: String,
  }
  ```
- Provide helper constructors and display implementations via `std::fmt::Display` and `std::error::Error`.
- Ensure lexer carries line/column counters, updating on each newline and token; attach this to errors.
- For layout and rendering errors, include contextual information where feasible (e.g., node id, diagram type).
- Enforce a no-panic policy:
  - Use `debug_assert!` only for internal invariants; never `unwrap()`/`expect()` on user data.
  - Rust clippy lints: enable `#![deny(clippy::unwrap_used, clippy::expect_used)]` in core modules.
- Provide an ergonomic error display:
  ```text
  Parse error at line 3, column 10: expected identifier after 'graph'
  ```
- Optionally, behind `serde` feature, errors may be serializable for tooling integration.

Pseudo-code for line/column tracking in lexer:
```rust
struct Lexer<'a> {
    src: &'a str,
    idx: usize,
    line: usize,
    col: usize,
}

impl<'a> Lexer<'a> {
    fn bump(&mut self) -> Option<char> {
        let ch = self.src[self.idx..].chars().next()?;
        self.idx += ch.len_utf8();
        if ch == '\n' {
            self.line += 1;
            self.col = 1;
        } else {
            self.col += 1;
        }
        Some(ch)
    }
}
```

